This article discusses the steps that the Obama Administration is taking to advance equal pay on the seventh anniversary of the Lilly Ledbetter Fair Pay Act. The median wage of a woman working full-time year-round in the US is 79% of a man's median earnings. The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC) is proposing to annually collect summary pay data by gender, race, and ethnicity from businesses with 100 or more employees. The President is also calling on Congress to pass the Paycheck Fairness Act and urging states and employers to take action to advance pay equality. The Council of Economic Advisers is releasing a report on the gender pay gap. The White House will host a summit on "The United State of Women" to mark progress made on behalf of women and discuss solutions to challenges they still face. The article also highlights other steps taken by the Obama Administration to combat the pay gap and support working families.